4th, In order to set men free to study facts, it was necessary to deliver thern froin the pemicious subjection to authority, to which they had so long been enslaved. Here and there throughout the Middle Ages, a solitary thinker, like Roget Bacon, may have asserted his independence, and, during the century preceding Bacon’s time, the murmurs of discontent had been becoming loud and frequent, but it required a clear, shrill voice, like that of the author of the Great Instauration, effectually to awaken men from their slumber. Bacon seems to have been thoroughly impressed with the feeling that there

was no hope for human fortunes, unless these bonds could be broken; and hence the tone of intended and conscious exaggeration with
